### Overview of the approach

The codebase is small and self-contained. The right error-signaling pattern for this size is **thrown typed errors**, not a Result/Either wrapper. A single `ServiceError` class (carrying an HTTP status code and a message) is thrown from service functions and caught once in each route handler. This keeps service functions with clean, natural return types, avoids `if (result.ok)` noise at every call site, and requires no third-party dependencies. It scales well to this number of routes.

---

### Step 1: Define the `ServiceError` class

This is not a new file — it belongs in `src/services/productService.ts` or a shared location. Because both service files need it, define it **once** and export it from `src/services/productService.ts` so `orderService.ts` can import it from there. Alternatively (and more cleanly), define it in a dedicated `src/services/errors.ts` and import it in both service files.

**`src/services/errors.ts`** (new file — one class, no external deps)

